    "text": "Go for the long run. A side stitch — that stabbing cramp under the ribs that eases when you slow down and disappears after the run — is a benign, boringly common running problem, usually tied to eating too close to the start or to breathing pattern at higher effort. Your data is genuinely good: recovery at 70%, HRV of 74 ms above your baseline near 71 ms, resting heart rate at 54 bpm, and 8 hours of sleep. To make a repeat less likely, leave a couple of hours after any solid meal, start the run conversational, and try exhaling as the foot opposite the stitch side lands. One distinction worth naming since it was in your torso: a stitch is sharp, breath-linked, and gone shortly after stopping — pressure or squeezing in the chest that lingers or spreads is a different thing entirely and belongs with a doctor.",
